-- #619 (declared-only) + #607 punch-list item 4: the exotic CROSS-PAIRING the
-- pair-shattered coverage test under-checks. `crossHelper` DECLARES `Ix a b` and
-- `Ix c d`; its body `ix w z` (w : a, z : d) induces the JOINT `Ix a d`, which is
-- NOT a declared predicate — yet every one of its arguments (a from `Ix a b`, d
-- from `Ix c d`) does appear in some declared predicate, so the per-argument pair
-- subset test passes and the joint constraint slips through.
--
-- Under the pre-#619 UNION the inferred `Ix a d` was MERGED into the scheme and
-- propagated to callers (silent widening of a signature). Declared-only sources the
-- scheme SOLELY from the declared `=>` (so `Ix a d` is never propagated), and the
-- vector-valued coverage check (censusSuperCloseVec / reportUncoveredVec) rejects the
-- binding: a body needing more than its signature declares is a def-site type error.
-- .expected = REJECT: `Could not deduce 'Ix a d' from the signature of 'crossHelper'`.
interface Ix a i where
  ix : a -> i -> Int

impl Ix Int Int where
  ix a i = a + i

crossHelper : (Ix a b, Ix c d) => a -> b -> c -> d -> Int
crossHelper w x y z = ix w z

main = println (crossHelper 1 2 3 4)
